text: In 2016, I was in a nearby city of the capital city of Ethiopia. I had diner at a house that owners used to sell home cooked street food, on my way to the rented house I was staying I realised I lost my passport and some hundred dollars and returned back. Each person pointed to another till I ended up at a bar who gave me my belongings. But soon before I reached my house I had three men follow me and asking me to reward them for helping find my stuff but they were asking for too much money and they cornered me to the wall of a store which was about to close. I decided to go inside and kept saying no I will not give you what you ask for. But it seemed that they were too hungry that if they had me there alone, who knows what they were capable of. Because this pressure kept on going for about 10 minutes and they wouldn't give up. One of them was very tall and big, all three of them were in there mid forties. Unlike in developed countries, if something happens to someone it is not forensically investigated so criminals are more confident in their mind to do what they want. So eventually they left me after they kept pressing me. Around there early on people go home streetlights are limited and people can hide in the dark. Always heard becareful it's not as safe as you think but that day I seen it for myself.
